Depends on the region and culture within the region.
The Pueblo, until the end anyways, were fully sedentary growing corn, beans, and peppers, and squash, while fishing the rivers and hunting for meat.
Just about a hundred miles north is the Great Plains and there fully nomadic buffalo-followers would rise and be spat out into Mexico or the Deep South via Texas. (The Aztec culture probably originated in Utah, before learning agriculture in Texas and then being cast out of their lands by the Apache and Karankawa, who also originated in Utah.) Though the best "gradient" society of Native Americans were the Mississippian peoples, who lived along the Mississippi river and its tributaries (the culture died out in Oklahoma). Some of the Mississippian cultures were advanced enough to have copper mines, others had Priest-King kingdoms that could levy armies as high as 10,000 during their golden age. However, Wars with Plains Indians and the Karankawa drove all but the Caddo and Witchita into extinction before the white man even arrived, the Caddo survived through isolation, and the Witchita abandoned civilization and waged wars with the Plains Indians,
